    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-03-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-03-11T12:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.63/520: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Austria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-11T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 11, 1938—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 11—3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>62. British Minister instructed by his Government that it informed Ribbentrop
                    today of serious impression which would be created in England by such direct
                    interference in internal affairs of Austria as foreseen by German ultimatum.
                    Ribbentrop’s attitude not encouraging but he consented to telephone Berlin. The
                    British Minister was cautioned by his Government against accepting any
                    responsibility for Schuschnigg’s decision.</p>
                <p>French Minister has so far received no reply from his Government but according to
                    Hornbostel Austrian Minister in Paris saw Léger who advised Austrian Government
                    to play for as much time as possible. <pb facs="0430" n="422" xml:id="pg_422"/>
                    Action might be concerted with England and Italy. If not “France would march
                    alone.” Italian attitude evasive if not negative. Gratz reliably reported to be
                    “occupied” by Austrian Army.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
